WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.640 --> 00:00:02.960
Deep within the heart of Asian Russia,

00:00:02.960 --> 00:00:07.840
a 640 kilometer long gigantic lake&nbsp;
is connecting the Sayan and Stanovoy

00:00:07.840 --> 00:00:14.120
Mountains of southern Siberia. This is Lake&nbsp;
Baikal. And while it's not the largest lake

00:00:14.120 --> 00:00:19.120
in the world, its geographical quirks and&nbsp;
peculiarities easily make it the most unique one.

00:00:19.760 --> 00:00:23.000
In this video we will first have a&nbsp;
look at lake Baikal's key geographical

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:26.560
features and see how it compares to&nbsp;
the other great lakes of this planet,

00:00:26.560 --> 00:00:31.120
before diving deeper into its origin&nbsp;
story and its extraordinary anomalies.

00:00:31.120 --> 00:00:36.440
Chapter 1: Lake Baikal in Numbers
With an area of just under 32 thousand square

00:00:36.440 --> 00:00:42.120
kilometers, or roughly the size of Belgium, Lake&nbsp;
Baikal ranks as the 7th largest lake in the world,

00:00:42.120 --> 00:00:47.280
just after the Caspian Sea and the North American&nbsp;
and African Great Lakes. But where it lacks in

00:00:47.280 --> 00:00:53.720
surface area, Lake Baikal compensates in depth.&nbsp;
Lying at an elevation of 450 meter above sea

00:00:53.720 --> 00:00:59.280
level, the deepest point of the lake bottom&nbsp;
reaches to almost 1200 meter below the sea level,

00:00:59.280 --> 00:01:06.000
giving lake Baikal a total depth of 1640 meter&nbsp;
and making it the deepest lake in the world.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:11.440
This combination of depth, area, and steep,&nbsp;
canyon-like walls have collected an immense

00:01:11.440 --> 00:01:17.120
volume of water within the lake's boundaries.&nbsp;
Coming from the South and East, the Selenga,

00:01:17.120 --> 00:01:22.680
Bargusin and Upper Angara River are draining a&nbsp;
large chunk of northern Mongolia and the Russian

00:01:22.680 --> 00:01:27.480
Republic of Buryatia into the lake, giving&nbsp;
it a volume larger than all the water in the

00:01:27.480 --> 00:01:34.160
American Great Lakes combined and constituting&nbsp;
22% of all surface freshwater on planet earth.

00:01:34.160 --> 00:01:38.560
While lying on the southern outskirts of the&nbsp;
Siberian tundra, the climate around the lake

00:01:38.560 --> 00:01:46.160
is no less arctic. Winter temperatures average&nbsp;
a quite uncomfortable -21°C or -6° Fahrenheit,

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:52.320
with a summer average in August barely&nbsp;
surpassing 11° Celsius or 52° Fahrenheit.

00:01:52.320 --> 00:01:55.360
These rough climatic conditions, paired&nbsp;
with the mountainous surroundings of

00:01:55.360 --> 00:02:00.280
the lake are a big factor for the seemingly&nbsp;
complete absence of significant developments

00:02:00.280 --> 00:02:06.240
around the lake. Only 40 towns have sprung up&nbsp;
along the over 2.000 kilometer long shoreline with

00:02:06.240 --> 00:02:11.720
just a single one of these reaching over 20.000&nbsp;
residents. The ones that do permanently live here,

00:02:11.720 --> 00:02:16.000
have often done so since the early iron&nbsp;
age, like on Baikal's largest Island,

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:22.480
Olkhon. Around 1750 Buryats call this rocky&nbsp;
outcrop their home, practicing shamanism and

00:02:22.480 --> 00:02:27.120
Buddhism, far away from the stereotypical&nbsp;
Russian culture. The land they live on,

00:02:27.120 --> 00:02:32.240
with 800 meter steep drops plunging from the&nbsp;
highest point of the island into Lake Baikal is

00:02:32.240 --> 00:02:37.400
also a perfect depiction of the tectonic past of&nbsp;
the region, which has created this natural wonder

00:02:37.400 --> 00:02:42.400
in the first place, bringing us to
Chapter 2: Lake Baikal's Creation

00:02:42.400 --> 00:02:47.440
The topographic composition of earth's surface&nbsp;
is constantly changing. But in this never ending

00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:52.200
dance of the elements, with erosion from wind&nbsp;
and water, the unstoppable march and retreat

00:02:52.200 --> 00:02:57.560
of glaciers, volcanic eruptions or even human&nbsp;
activity there is one shaping factor like no

00:02:57.560 --> 00:03:01.535
other and it's this one, which stands behind&nbsp;
the creation of Lake Baikal.

00:03:01.535 --> 00:03:03.036
Plate Tectonics

00:03:03.537 --> 00:03:07.957
The typical map of the world's plate boundaries&nbsp;
used for studying in schools, is typically a

00:03:07.957 --> 00:03:13.003
bit of an oversimplification, with many microplates 
and rift zones being left out.

00:03:13.003 --> 00:03:18.160
Especially around the Pacific Ring of Fire. Incorporating&nbsp;
these as well however, quickly reveals

00:03:18.160 --> 00:03:23.200
the tectonic activity which has shaped these&nbsp;
inner Asian mountain ranges, and Lake Baikal.

00:03:23.200 --> 00:03:27.760
Around the north-western boundary of the&nbsp;
Amurian microplate, a combination of divergent

00:03:27.760 --> 00:03:32.840
and transform plate movements are separating it&nbsp;
from the Eurasian tectonic plate with around 4mm

00:03:32.840 --> 00:03:37.360
per year. The combination of these motions is&nbsp;
the cause for regular earthquakes in the region,

00:03:37.360 --> 00:03:42.571
whenever the fault zone slips from the lateral&nbsp;
movement. At the same time the divergent movement

00:03:42.571 --> 00:03:47.283
thins out the continental plates along the rift, 
significantly increasing&nbsp;the occurrence of geothermal

00:03:47.283 --> 00:03:49.920
features around Lake Baikal, which is one of the primary

00:03:49.920 --> 00:03:54.400
tourist attractions of the region, and major&nbsp;
earthquakes which have devastated parts of Russia,

00:03:54.400 --> 00:03:59.720
Mongolia and even China can be drawn back to&nbsp;
this plate boundary. With the advent of GPS,

00:04:00.240 --> 00:04:03.920
the speed of the plates can be tracked&nbsp;
quite accurately today, and knowing that

00:04:03.920 --> 00:04:08.800
the divergence occurs at roughly 3-4mm per&nbsp;
year, the creation of the lake as a whole

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:13.800
can be traced back to around 25 to 30 million&nbsp;
years ago. This has also been confirmed with

00:04:13.800 --> 00:04:18.800
deep boreholes into the lake bed, where millions&nbsp;
of years of sediment strata have been unearthed,

00:04:18.800 --> 00:04:23.440
which also gives a detailed insight into&nbsp;
climatic developments of the distant past.

00:04:23.440 --> 00:04:27.600
With this age, having originated roughly&nbsp;
halfway between now and the extinction of

00:04:27.600 --> 00:04:32.560
the non-avian dinosaurs, Lake Baikal is actually&nbsp;
considered an ancient lake and according to the

00:04:32.560 --> 00:04:37.920
most common consensus, it is the oldest lake that&nbsp;
is currently sitting on earth's surface. There is

00:04:37.920 --> 00:04:43.240
one other contender in eastern Kazakhstan whose&nbsp;
age is estimated at around 70 million years,

00:04:43.240 --> 00:04:47.160
but a lack of evidence for Lake&nbsp;
Zaysan still favors Lake Baikal.

00:04:47.160 --> 00:04:52.440
So far we have covered that Lake Baikal is&nbsp;
the deepest, most voluminous and also the oldest

00:04:52.440 --> 00:04:56.520
lake of the planet, but there are actually&nbsp;
many more peculiarities about the pearl of&nbsp;

00:04:56.520 --> 00:05:01.280
Siberia where it is so different from the typical&nbsp;
lakes, which we will have a closer look at in

00:05:01.280 --> 00:05:06.960
Chapter 3: Oddities of Lake Baikal
A large catchment area and hundreds

00:05:06.960 --> 00:05:12.600
of smaller streams are continuously feeding into&nbsp;
Lake Baikal, with these inflows making up 85% of

00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:17.880
its water budget in a typical year, while the rest&nbsp;
is covered by direct precipitation onto the lake.

00:05:17.880 --> 00:05:22.520
Once the water enters into the hollow, it has a&nbsp;
typical residence in the lake of over 300 years,

00:05:22.520 --> 00:05:27.196
before the average molecule gets flushed out&nbsp;
again through its only outlet, the Angara River.

00:05:27.196 --> 00:05:33.920
In this time, the water is exposed to the harsh subpolar climate&nbsp;
of Siberia, and undergoes a distinct annual cycle.

00:05:33.920 --> 00:05:38.280
Starting in deep winter, when lake Baikal&nbsp;
is covered with a solid slab of ice,

00:05:38.280 --> 00:05:44.040
the water temperature at the surface hovers around&nbsp;
freezing and then gradually increases towards 3.8°

00:05:44.040 --> 00:05:49.880
Celsius at a depth of around 200 meters. As spring&nbsp;
comes around the ice masses on the surface slowly

00:05:49.880 --> 00:05:54.560
recede and the upper layers of water quickly&nbsp;
heat up. At a certain moment in early June,

00:05:54.560 --> 00:05:59.640
the temperature distribution throughout the&nbsp;entire
lake homogenizes at around 4°C,

00:05:59.640 --> 00:06:03.960
during which time the oxygen-rich waters of&nbsp;
the surface sink to the bottom of the lake,

00:06:03.960 --> 00:06:06.760
supplying all stratas with vital oxygene.

00:06:06.760 --> 00:06:08.720
Once summer is in full swing, the temperature

00:06:08.720 --> 00:06:13.400
stratification completely reverses with&nbsp;
the surface measuring averages of 16°&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:13.400 --> 00:06:17.960
celsius while the lake layers below&nbsp;
200 meters remain at a chilly 3.8°.

00:06:19.240 --> 00:06:22.560
This annually recurring pattern with&nbsp;
two complete water exchanges between

00:06:22.560 --> 00:06:27.160
the surface and lake bottom, has ensured a&nbsp;
robust food web to exist within the lake,

00:06:27.160 --> 00:06:32.360
in which copepods create a self cleaning ecosystem&nbsp;
and in which no one species of algae can blossom

00:06:32.360 --> 00:06:36.600
too excessively. These filter feeders, which&nbsp;
are even devouring plankton when the lake is

00:06:36.600 --> 00:06:40.960
frozen over completely, together with generally&nbsp;
low levels of phosphorus and nitrogen, actually

00:06:40.960 --> 00:06:45.680
create some of the clearest water in the world,&nbsp;
with total dissolved solids only contributing

00:06:45.680 --> 00:06:51.680
96 mg per liter of lake water. For reference, the&nbsp;
World Health Organization recommends levels below

00:06:51.680 --> 00:06:58.320
500 for drinking water, and the US tap water&nbsp;
only averages TDS levels of around 350 mg/l.

00:06:59.600 --> 00:07:03.920
The low turbidity also allows for exceptional&nbsp;
views into the lake while it is frozen over

00:07:03.920 --> 00:07:10.280
for nearly half the year. With a typical ice&nbsp;
thickness of 1 to 1.5 meter, or 3 to 5 feet,

00:07:10.280 --> 00:07:14.960
it is completely safe to traverse the frozen&nbsp;
wasteland even by car during peak winter. The

00:07:14.960 --> 00:07:19.760
combination of rapid freezing and harsh winds&nbsp;
on the ice surface also create some mesmerizing

00:07:19.760 --> 00:07:24.400
formations across the surface, ranging from&nbsp;
methane bubble columns to pedestals for rocks

00:07:24.400 --> 00:07:29.920
and icicles, which has propelled lake Baikal as&nbsp;
a winter tourist destination in recent years.

00:07:29.920 --> 00:07:34.440
During the summer, the interest of tourists shifts&nbsp;
more to the mountainous surroundings of the lake,

00:07:34.440 --> 00:07:38.760
which has over time been protected more and&nbsp;
more. While the Soviet Union wasn’t particularly

00:07:38.760 --> 00:07:43.263
known for protecting their lakes, looking at what they 
have done to the&nbsp;Aral Sea for example,

00:07:43.263 --> 00:07:45.138
Lake Baikal has been treated way better

00:07:45.138 --> 00:07:49.520
in the past century. The first nature reserve&nbsp;
of the entire country was set up on the north

00:07:49.520 --> 00:07:54.960
eastern shoreline, around the delta of the river&nbsp;
Barguzin in 1916, and many more nature reserves,

00:07:54.960 --> 00:07:59.040
national parks and game reserves followed&nbsp;
in the coming century, which now protects

00:07:59.040 --> 00:08:03.120
over 50% of Lake Baikal's shoreline.
Despite all these efforts however,

00:08:03.120 --> 00:08:07.240
economic prospects are continuously&nbsp;
challenging nature preservation. So far,

00:08:07.240 --> 00:08:11.960
local and international activist groups have&nbsp;
successfully rerouted a proposed oil pipeline

00:08:11.960 --> 00:08:15.800
along the earthquake-prone shoreline of Lake&nbsp;
Baikal, whose leakage into the lake could

00:08:15.800 --> 00:08:20.960
have detrimental impacts on the biota. Further a&nbsp;
pulp and paper mill, which has dumped production

00:08:20.960 --> 00:08:27.480
waste and bleach straight into the lake for nearly half a 
century has&nbsp;been closed since 2013 due to bankruptcy,

00:08:27.480 --> 00:08:32.440
and while the 15.000 tons of toxic waste which&nbsp;
has been dumped into the lake dilutes well through

00:08:32.440 --> 00:08:37.200
the vast volume, some changes through&nbsp;
the last decades have been noticed.

00:08:37.200 --> 00:08:41.160
The expansion of putrid algae, and the&nbsp;
disappearance of several endemic fish and

00:08:41.160 --> 00:08:45.480
sponge species are a byproduct of the local&nbsp;
pollution but, also the general warming of

00:08:45.480 --> 00:08:50.640
the climate and lake water, which throws off&nbsp;
the intricate ballet of water and sediments.

00:08:50.640 --> 00:08:54.520
How global warming will further impact these&nbsp;
developments can not be said right now,

00:08:54.520 --> 00:08:59.840
but one thing is for sure. The fragile cycles&nbsp;
of flora, fauna and the water itself have stood

00:08:59.840 --> 00:09:03.720
the test of time for 30 million years now&nbsp;
and the lake will not disappear any time

00:09:03.720 --> 00:09:08.800
soon. The question is rather how the beauty and&nbsp;
magnificence of this Siberian giant can bring

00:09:08.800 --> 00:09:14.480
prosperity to the region without damaging it and&nbsp;
how it will adapt to the future that lies ahead.

00:09:14.480 --> 00:09:18.680
I hope you learned something from this overview&nbsp;
of Lake Baikal. If you want to learn more about

00:09:18.680 --> 00:09:22.280
the region where the Baikal’s waters are&nbsp;
coming from, I can recommend this video

00:09:22.280 --> 00:09:26.560
about the geography of Mongolia, or watch&nbsp;
what YouTube thinks is best for you here.

00:09:26.560 --> 00:09:29.360
See you in the next one, cheers

